    "summary": "The Battle of Aegospotami (405 BC) was the final naval engagement of the [[event:1010|Peloponnesian War]], in which the Spartan admiral Lysander destroyed the Athenian fleet almost entirely while it was beached on the Thracian shore of the Hellespont. The battle effectively ended the war by cutting off Athens's grain supply from the Black Sea region, forcing the city to surrender the following year.\n\nLysander had spent years patiently rebuilding Sparta's naval power with Persian funding, and he was a cunning commander who waited for the right moment. For four days, the Athenian fleet under multiple generals challenged Lysander to battle; he declined each time. On the fifth day, as the Athenians pulled ashore in disorder to forage for food, Lysander's fleet struck. Most of the Athenian ships were captured with minimal resistance; only a handful escaped under Conon. Some 3,000–4,000 Athenian captives were executed by Lysander, who singled them out for retribution over Athenian wartime atrocities. The destruction of the fleet was the final blow that led to Athens's [[event:1016|Surrender of Athens]].",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Aegospotami",
